name: L-glutamic acid 5-benzyl ester

In this case, the target compound is L-glutamic acid 5-benzyl ester. The basic units to consider are benzene and glutamic acid. Benzene has a melting point of 5.5°C, and glutamic acid has a melting point of approximately 200°C due to its ability to form a zwitterion, which increases intermolecular forces. The benzyl group is a phenyl with an additional CH2, which could increase the melting point due to the aromatic system's stabilization and the increase in the molecular weight. We estimate this may increase the melting point by approximately 10°C. The ester group typically can't participate in hydrogen bonding as a donor, which may reduce the melting point compared to the acid. The ester may reduce the melting point in comparison to free glutamic acid by around -25°C due to the lack of strong hydrogen bonding. Putting these adjustments together: Benzene base (+5.5), additional molecular weight from the benzyl group (+10), and the reduction in hydrogen bonding ability due to the ester substituent (-25), we estimate a predicted melting point for the target compound.
